05215nam a22008175i 9780231536103DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2013    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315361037 a10.7312/wehr165122doi  a(DE-B1597)459432  a(OCoLC)1013963044  a(OCoLC)979575151  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDS247.A138bW44 2015 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a953.0542231 aWehrey, Frederic, eauthor.10aSectarian Politics in the Gulf :bFrom the Iraq War to the Arab Uprisings /cFrederic Wehrey. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource :bB&W Illus.: 1  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in Middle East Politics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tList of Abbreviations -- tPART I. THE ROOTS OF SECTARIANISM -- t1. Governance, Society, and Identity in the Gulf -- t2. The Long Shadow of the Iranian Revolution -- tPART II. BAHRAIN -- t3. Debating Participation -- t4. Sectarian Balancing -- t5. Into the Abyss -- tPART III. SAUDI ARABIA -- t6. Loyalties Under Fire -- t7. Under Siege -- t8. Waving ʿUthman's Shirt -- tPART IV. KUWAIT -- t9. Renegotiating a Ruling Bargain -- t10. Tilting Toward Repression -- t11. A Balancing Act Goes Awry -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of Foreign Policy's Best Five Books of 2013, chosen by Marc Lynch of The Middle East ChannelBeginning with the 2003 invasion of Iraq and concluding with the aftermath of the 2011 Arab uprisings, Frederic M. Wehrey investigates the roots of the Shi'a-Sunni divide now dominating the Persian Gulf's political landscape. Focusing on three Gulf states affected most by sectarian tensions-Bahrain, Saudi Arabia, and Kuwait-Wehrey identifies the factors that have exacerbated or tempered sectarianism, including domestic political institutions, the media, clerical establishments, and the contagion effect of external regional events, such as the Iraq war, the 2006 Lebanon conflict, the Arab uprisings, and Syria's civil war.In addition to his analysis, Wehrey builds a historical narrative of Shi'a activism in the Arab Gulf since 2003, linking regional events to the development of local Shi'a strategies and attitudes toward citizenship, political reform, and transnational identity. He finds that, while the Gulf Shi'a were inspired by their coreligionists in Iraq, Iran, and Lebanon, they ultimately pursued greater rights through a nonsectarian, nationalist approach. He also discovers that sectarianism in the region has largely been the product of the institutional weaknesses of Gulf states, leading to excessive alarm by entrenched Sunni elites and calculated attempts by regimes to discredit Shi'a political actors as proxies for Iran, Iraq, or Lebanese Hizballah. Wehrey conducts interviews with nearly every major Shi'a leader, opinion shaper, and activist in the Gulf Arab states, as well as prominent Sunni voices, and consults diverse Arabic-language sources.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aShīʻahxRelationsxSunnites. 0aShīʻahxRelationsxSunnites. 0aSunnitesxRelationsxShīʻah. 0aSunnitesxRelationsxShīʻah. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/wehr16512423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231536103.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978